-- 2010-10-20T06:35:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-20/pko-shares-trade-ex-dividend-bogdanka-wins-order-central-europe-equitie.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in central European
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names.
Share prices are from the last close.  Poland’s  WIG20 Index  fell 1.4 percent, the Czech  PX Index 
rose 0.3 percent as did Hungary’s  BUX Index .  Enea SA  (ENA PW): Poland wants to complete talks with two
bidders for a 51 percent stake in the country’s third-largest
utility by Oct. 26, allowing them to pursue unlimited due
diligence in the meantime, and then initial an agreement by Oct.
28, Puls Biznesu said, without citing anyone. Enea declined 0.2
percent to 22.95 zloty.  Lubelski Wegiel Bogdanka SA  (LWB PW): The Polish coal
producer that’s the subject of a takeover bid from New World
Resources NV signed a 19-year, 12.5 billion-zloty ($4.36
billion) agreement to supply coal to a unit of power utility
Energa SA. Bogdanka slipped 0.2 percent to 105.4 zloty.  PKN Orlen SA  (PKN PW): Seven companies have expressed
initial interest in the Polish oil refiner’s Lithuanian unit,
Puls Biznesu reported, without saying where it got the
information. Orlen fell 1.1 percent to 39.15 zloty.  PKO Bank Polski SA  (PKO PW): Shares of Poland’s biggest
bank will start trading without the right to the 2009 dividend
of 1.9 zloty per share. PKO dropped 1.3 percent to 46 zloty.  To contact the reporters on this story:
 Pawel Kozlowski  in Warsaw 
